column1: I matched as well as I could, meaning that in most cases the samples are from identical plants, but not in all cases. In some cases, they are different individuals but from the same station. Good enough! ;-)

In some cases, I didn't have any of the species or didn't have as many replicates, so I named them n/a/ in my additions for those rows. In some cases, I actually had more samples than you, so I added rows.
Cells in your spreadsheet highlighted in reddish tone means there was a typo and I fixed it.

Blue highlight means that there is some confusion in the names. One cell says Myriogramme mangini but to following cells say "laingioides" for the species. I think that is a left-over from Chuck's confusion about Myriogramme (mangini) versis Rhodokrambe (laingioides). After later inspection in his lab, he decided that they were all Myrigramme mangini. I added my Myriogramme mangini values to those cells but you may want to change your species names in those.

Lastly, I think there is still some confusion between Phyllophora and Callophyllis (bright yellow highlights and red font). I know we went through those changes at some point but maybe they didn't get translated into this particular spreadsheet? I added my Callophyllis or Phyllophora (whichever way the change went) in the same rows and highlighted the name changes. Let me know if you want to go through those again to make sure there is enough replication of both species. Those are particularly interesting (I think) because they are so close morphologically, but at least isotopically, they are vastly different. I wonder how the fatty acids play out for them....
